node.text: Topped with a colorful mix of tropical fruit, toasted nuts, and seeds, these open-faced chocolate disks from chef Paola Velez (@smallorchids) can be made ahead and served right from the fridge. Plus, they come together with the help of none other than your microwave! Find out how to make Tropical Mendiants by visiting this link https://bit.ly/2VLcZMq or tap the link in our bio for the recipe!

node.text: The secret to these flavor-packed, plant-based nachos from @chefmamacass2 are two different kinds of lentils: black and red. Crispy pita chips are smothered with an the irresistable feta queso, layers of pepper-tinged lentil chili, rose harissa-spiked pickled cabbage, and dollops of yogurt. It's definitely a dish worth sharing. Tap the link in our bio for the recipe!

node.title: FWCooks | Loaded Pita Nachos with Lentil Chili and Feta Queso

node.text:
Happy birthday, Julia Child! The chef who brought French cooking into the kitchens and television screens of the American public with her book "Mastering the Art of French Cooking" and her PBS show "The French Chef" in the 1960s and 1970s, would have turned 109-years-old today.

While people usually associate Julia with complex French dishes, many of her recipes for F&W (she became a contributor in 1989), such as her Roast Chicken and Ham Steaks in Madeira Sauce, weren’t complicated at all. Today we are sharing a few of Julia's contributions to the F&W library over the years. 

Now, Child will once again be in the spotlight as a new documentary "Julia" aims to memorialize her legacy and impact on the food and media industries through chef interviews, never-before-seen footage, and Child's own words to illuminate her life and impact. Swipe to see more and click the link in bio to get the recipes!
📸: Schlesinger Library/@juliachildfoundation 
📸: @conpoulos_photographer 
📸: @gregdupree

Everything gets a touch of heat from serrano peppers and pan-seared tofu. Tap the link in bio for the recipe! 🥗: @hughacheson 📸: @conpoulos_photographer

node.text: The key to this Brothy Braised Chicken Thighs with Fennel and Pernod recipe is the slow-rendered fat. Not only does it make for a stunning piece of poultry, it also seeps into the veggies, melting them to an irresistibly silky texture that might just outshine the main. Tap the link in bio for everything you need to make this one-pot wonder! 🍗: @coluhenry 📸: @antonisachilleos

node.text: It’s National Filet Mignon Day, so what better way to celebrate than with a classic Steak Diane recipe. This style calls for sautéing thinly sliced or pounded filet mignon in butter and then flambéing and basting it in a rich Cognac sauce. Tap the link in bio to celebrate with steak tonight! 🥩: @emeril 📸: @dmalosh
